%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% ABSTRACT - not done yet  %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\begin{abstract}
Fast and effective incident response is essential to prevent adversarial cyberattacks. Autonomous Cyber Defense (ACD) aims to automate response through AI agents. While prior work established the first integration of LLMs in multi-agent environments like CybORG CAGE 4, performance often lagged behind Reinforcement Learning (RL). In this paper, we extend this framework by introducing a \textbf{Chain-of-Self-Correction (CoSC)} mechanism and a high-performance local inference architecture. Our results demonstrate a transformative shift: our reasoning-based hybrid agent (DeepSeek-R1-1.5b) achieved a mean reward of \textbf{-477.5}, reaching full performance parity with specialized RL experts (-493.0). Furthermore, our system maintained a \textbf{zero-adversary-impact} record across 1,000 steps, proving that logic-hardened LLMs are viable candidates for production-grade ACD systems.
\end{abstract}

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%% INTRODUCTION - not done yet %%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\section{Problem Definition and Motivation}
The contemporary cybersecurity landscape is witnessing an escalation in threat complexity at an unprecedented pace. According to the 2026 Check Point Cyber Security Report, organizations faced a record average of 1,968 weekly attacks in 2025,a 70\% increase since 2023. This alarming volume of incidents makes manual response by human operators nearly impossible, leading to analyst burnout and increased Mean Time to Remediate (MTTR). Consequently, there is an urgent demand for Autonomous Cyber Defense (ACD) systems capable of real-time, multi-agent coordination without constant human oversight.

Traditionally, ACD research has been dominated by Reinforcement Learning (RL) agents. While RL models provide high execution speeds and mathematical optimization, they function as "black-boxes," offering little to no transparency regarding their decision-making logic. In critical infrastructure defense, this lack of explainability poses (reasoning) significant trust and safety risks. The recent study by Castro et al., \textit{"Large Language Models are Autonomous Cyber Defenders"}~\cite{arXiv:2505.04843v2}, proposed a paradigm shift by utilizing Large Language Models (LLMs) as reasoning engines. LLMs leverage vast semantic knowledge to provide human-interpretable strategies and zero-shot adaptability to novel network topologies.

Despite these advantages, the original research highlighted a critical performance gap: RL agents still outperform LLM-based defenders in joint reward metrics. This performance deficit is often attributed to the high latency of LLM inference and the risk of \textbf{model hallucinations} during multi-step reasoning tasks. 

This gap provides the primary motivation for our work. In alignment with the course requirements, this paper aims to:
\begin{enumerate}
    \item Recreate the original LLM-defender framework within the CybORG environment.
    \item Implement an \textbf{experimental extension} that benchmarks the framework against the latest generation of reasoning-centric models (e.g. LLama4, DeepSeek-R1 and other available local models) while utilizing \textbf{Schema-Constrained Prompting} to eliminate action-space hallucinations.
    \item Evaluate whether structured reasoning optimizations can bridge the performance gap between semantic LLM agents and traditional RL-based models.
\end{enumerate}

\section{Background and Technical Foundations}
To evaluate the effectiveness of LLMs in autonomous cyber operations, it is essential to understand the underlying mechanisms of reinforcement learning, multi-agent coordination, and semantic reasoning within simulated environments.

\subsection{The CybORG and CAGE 4 Environment}
The primary testbed for this research is the \textbf{CybORG} environment, specifically the \textbf{CAGE 4} challenge. CybORG is a high-fidelity cybersecurity simulator that models complex network interactions using a Python-based Open AI Gym interface. In CAGE 4, the environment is framed as a Multi-Agent Reinforcement Learning (MARL) problem, where a "Blue Team" of automated defenders must cooperate to protect a corporate network against a sophisticated "Red Agent." The agents operate under a decentralized POMDP (Partially Observable Markov Decision Process), meaning each defender only has a limited view of the overall network state.

\subsection{The KEEP Agent Baseline}
The original study utilizes the \textbf{KEEP} (Knowledge-Enhanced Execution Policy) agent as the primary Reinforcement Learning baseline. Developed using the \textbf{Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO)} algorithm, KEEP was specifically designed and pre-trained to excel in previous CAGE iterations. It was selected for this study because it represents the state-of-the-art (SOTA) performance for traditional RL in this domain. By comparing LLM-driven defenders against KEEP, the researchers can measure the gap between general-purpose reasoning and specialized, environment-tuned automation.

\subsection{Multi-Agent Communication Protocols}
Coordination in CAGE 4 is facilitated through a restricted \textbf{8-bit (1-byte) communication vector} shared among Blue agents. This vector serves as a low-bandwidth signaling mechanism, allowing agents to broadcast status updates or perceived threat levels to neighboring defenders. A significant technical challenge in integrating LLMs involves the \textbf{Adapter Framework}, which must translate these abstract numerical vectors into natural language descriptions, such as "Agent 3 reports a high threat level", so the LLM can incorporate team-wide context into its decision-making process.

\subsection{LLMs as Autonomous Reasoning Agents}
Unlike traditional RL agents that require extensive training on millions of environment steps, Large Language Models (LLMs) function as zero-shot reasoning engines. By utilizing the aforementioned Adapter, the numerical observations from CybORG are translated into structured natural language prompts. Our experimental extension focuses on optimizing the \textbf{Chain of Thought (CoT)} processing within this framework. By implementing a "Chain-of-Self-Correction" mechanism, we aim to bridge the "Reality Gap" and improve the agent's ability to provide human-interpretable justifications while minimizing reasoning hallucinations.

