\section{Related Work}
 
This section reviews four papers that directly relate to our
work. Two focus on RL-based approaches that establish the
performance baselines we compare against, and two explore
LLM-based methods that tackle the hallucination and reasoning
challenges we aim to improve. For each paper we summarize
the methodology, dataset, performance, and limitations,
followed by a short comparison and a note on how the paper
directly contributes to our experimental extension.
Table~\ref{tab:related_work} provides a consolidated overview.
 
% ,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
\subsection{\textbf{Hierarchical Multi-Agent Reinforcement Learning
            for Cyber Network Defense (Singh et al., 2025)}}
% ,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
 
Singh et al.~\cite{arXiv:2410.17351} propose H-MARL, a
hierarchical MARL framework built on top of PPO~\cite{arXiv:1707.06347}
and evaluated on CybORG CAGE~4~\cite{CAGE4:2023}. The main
idea is to break the defense task into three sub-policies,
investigate, recover, and control traffic, each trained
separately using domain knowledge. A master policy then
coordinates which sub-policy to invoke. Two variants are
presented: H-MARL~Expert uses a hand-crafted IOC-based rule,
while H-MARL~Meta learns the master policy from frozen
sub-policies. The observation space is extended with Indicators
of Compromise~(IOCs), which alone improves reward by~42\%.
 
H-MARL~Expert achieves $-129.53 \pm 44.60$ average reward
against the default red agent in CAGE~4, which is the best
result among all compared methods. H-MARL~Meta converges
3--5$\times$ faster than a standard decentralized baseline.
The paper also defines four red-agent variants,
AggressiveFSM, StealthyFSM, ImpactFSM, and
DegradeServiceFSM, which are the same adversaries used
by Castro et al.~\cite{arXiv:2505.04843v2} and in our
experiments.
 
\textbf{Strengths:} Strong performance; transferable
sub-policies; interpretable defense metrics.
 
\textbf{Limitations:} Fully black-box; no reasoning or
explanations; breaks under probabilistic master-policy rules.
 
\textbf{Comparison:} We use the same adversary set. Unlike
H-MARL, our LLM agent explains each action in plain language,
which is important for real-world operator oversight.
 
\textbf{Contribution:} The four FSM red-agent variants are used
directly as our evaluation set. The IOC-based decision logic
--- recover if compromised, else investigate --- serves as a
reference for what correct reasoning looks like, which we
encode into our Chain-of-Self-Correction prompt template.
 
% ,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
\subsection{\textbf{Automated Cyber Defense with Generalizable
            Graph-Based RL Agents (King et al., 2025)}}
% ,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
 
King et al.~\cite{arXiv:2509.16151} tackle a known problem in
ACD: RL agents that are trained on one network topology fail
when the topology changes. Their solution is to represent the
network as a graph and process it with a Graph Convolutional
Network~(GCN), so the agent learns topology-independent
policies. Actions are defined as operations on graph nodes and
edges rather than a fixed list, which means the action space
naturally adapts when the network grows or shrinks. Three
variants are evaluated, and the best-performing inductive model
achieves a score of~$0.9955$ at~$|V|=40$ in Yawning Titan,
more than $4\times$ better than prior tabular methods. In
CAGE~4, the resulting KEEP model~\cite{KEEP:2025} is the
top non-heuristic submission, finishing fifth overall.
 
\textbf{Strengths:} Zero-shot generalization across topologies;
strong results in multiple environments; open-source.
 
\textbf{Limitations:} Still a black-box RL agent; no natural
language reasoning; large sim-to-real gap for real deployments.
 
\textbf{Comparison:} KEEP is the RL baseline in
Castro et al.~\cite{arXiv:2505.04843v2} and the benchmark we
aim to close the gap against. The performance gap between
KEEP~($\mu = -493$) and an all-LLM team~($\mu = -2547.2$)
is exactly the problem our work addresses.
 
\textbf{Contribution:} Understanding KEEP is essential for
interpreting the benchmark we evaluate against. Its strength
comes from graph-based generalization and millions of
environment-specific training steps, which explains why the
reward gap between KEEP~($\mu = -493$) and the LLM
baseline~($\mu = -2547.2$) exists. This context gives proper
weight to the improvements our prompting strategies achieve.
 
% ,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
\subsection{\textbf{Hallucination-Resistant Security Planning with a
            Large Language Model (Hammar et al., 2026)}}
% ,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
 
Hammar et al.~\cite{arXiv:2602.05279} address the hallucination
problem in LLM-based security management. Their framework
works by generating multiple candidate actions and checking
how consistent they are with each other. If the consistency
score falls below a threshold $\gamma$, the framework abstains
and instead collects feedback from a digital twin before trying
again. The authors prove formally that tuning $\gamma$
controls the hallucination probability. The framework uses a
fine-tuned DeepSeek-R1-14B model and is tested on 25 security
incidents across four public datasets. It reduces average
recovery time by up to 30\% compared to frontier LLMs, with
a hallucination rate of~$0.02$ versus~$0.06$ without the
abstention step.
 
\textbf{Strengths:} Formal hallucination guarantees;
significant improvement over larger frontier models.
 
\textbf{Limitations:} Only covers offline, sequential incident
response, not real-time multi-agent defense. Requires a
calibration dataset and a digital twin, which are not available
in CybORG CAGE~4.
 
\textbf{Comparison:} Castro et al.~\cite{arXiv:2505.04843v2}
report hallucination as the main LLM failure mode in CAGE~4.
Rather than relying on external infrastructure, we tackle the
same issue with Schema-Constrained Prompting and
Chain-of-Self-Correction, both of which work within a single
inference call.
 
\textbf{Contribution:} The idea that inconsistent outputs
signal hallucination directly inspires our
Chain-of-Self-Correction mechanism, where the LLM checks its
own reasoning before acting. Their hallucination rate
of~$0.02$ also gives us a concrete target to compare our
in-context approach against.
 
% ,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
\subsection{\textbf{In-Context Autonomous Network Incident Response
            (Gao et al., 2026)}}
% ,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,,
 
Gao et al.~\cite{arXiv:2602.13156} build an end-to-end LLM
agent for incident response using a single 14B-parameter model.
The agent covers four steps: understanding the current recovery
state, predicting what happens under different actions, picking
the best action via Monte-Carlo lookahead, and generating the
response command. The model is fine-tuned with LoRA on
50{,}000 labeled examples and adapts online by comparing
predicted versus actual alerts. It achieves a recovery time
of~$10.3$ actions on average, 23\% faster than frontier
LLMs, with an exact-match accuracy of~$0.98$.
 
\textbf{Strengths:} End-to-end pipeline without manual
modeling; strong accuracy after fine-tuning; handles
long-horizon tasks.
 
\textbf{Limitations:} The Monte-Carlo planning step is slow,
roughly 20 minutes per 5-action response on an A100 GPU.
This makes it incompatible with real-time environments like
CybORG. No multi-agent setting is tested.
 
\textbf{Comparison:} Gao et al.\ show that structured reasoning
combined with fine-tuning reduces hallucinations effectively.
We take a similar direction but without the fine-tuning cost
or the heavy planning overhead. Our approach is designed to
work inside CAGE~4's step-by-step action loop with no
additional infrastructure required.
 
\textbf{Contribution:} The four-step reasoning flow ---
perceive, reason, plan, act --- is the basis for our
Chain-of-Thought prompt template. The JSON-structured output
format directly informs our Schema-Constrained Prompting,
where a strict schema prevents the LLM from generating
invalid actions entirely.

