\section{Methodology}
This section details the technical framework of our study. To ensure scientific rigor and validity, our methodology is designed to \textbf{explicitly replicate the experimental environment established by Castro et al. [1]}, with particular focus on their 1 LLM + 4 RL blue agent configuration, which represented the most balanced and competitive setup in the original study. We strive for identical configuration settings, team compositions, and adversarial conditions to facilitate a direct comparison between the baseline performance and our proposed extensions.

\subsection{Agent Architecture and CoSC Extension}
Our autonomous defender is architected as a modular cognitive engine designed to bridge the semantic gap between raw network telemetry and high-level defensive maneuvers. 

Following the "Hybrid" configuration evaluated in the original study, we utilize a team consisting of \textbf{one LLM-driven agent} (Blue Agent 4) operating alongside \textbf{four pre-trained RL agents} (KEEP GNN PPO). The agents operate under a decentralized POMDP (Partially Observable Markov Decision Process).

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{The Adapter Interface:} We utilize a customized wrapper that translates CybORG’s numerical observation vectors into structured natural language. A significant enhancement in our implementation is the \textbf{IOC-Priority Encoding}. Instead of generic alerts, the adapter assigns a priority score (0-3) to each host based on Indicators of Compromise (IOCs), such as malicious file signatures and decoy service accesses.
    
    \item \textbf{Novel Extension, Chain-of-Self-Correction (CoSC):} To mitigate hallucinations, we implement an iterative self-correction loop. Before an action is committed, a preventative semantic gate validates the candidate command against detected host priorities. If a contradiction is detected—such as attempting a \texttt{Restore} on an uncompromised host—the agent triggers a re-generation cycle with explicit semantic feedback.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Infrastructure and Distributed Inference}
To evaluate the feasibility of enterprise-grade "Private Autonomous Defense," we utilize a distributed inference setup that separates simulation logic from heavy neural processing. 

The reasoning engines, \textbf{DeepSeek-R1-1.5b} and \textbf{Qwen-2.5-7b}, are hosted on a  research server. This infrastructure is equipped with an \textbf{NVIDIA RTX 4080 GPU} and \textbf{64GB of RAM}. Models are served via the Ollama framework. The simulation environment executes on a local orchestration node, communicating with the inference server.

\subsection{Experimental Environment and Parity Protocol}
To maintain \textbf{full parity with the original experiment}, we configured the testbed to match the "Strict Baseline" parameters:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Testbed:} The CybORG CAGE 4 Enterprise Network.
    \item \textbf{Volume and Duration:} We executed \textbf{2 episodes} with a fixed horizon of \textbf{500 steps} per episode, totaling \textbf{1,000 action decisions} per model configuration.
    \item \textbf{Adversary Strategy:} All agents were evaluated against the default \textbf{FiniteStateRedAgent}, matching the adversary used for the hybrid evaluations in Figure 4 of the original paper [1].
    \item \textbf{Hyperparameters:} Consistent with Castro et al., we set the model \textbf{temperature to 1.0} to evaluate the inherent reasoning capabilities without context-dependency optimization.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Evaluation Metrics}
demonstrate how the calculate was done - - show the equations***
We quantify the effectiveness of our extension using metrics established across the reviewed literature:
\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Joint Reward ($\mu$):} The primary indicator of team efficacy.
    \item \textbf{Standard Deviation ($\sigma$):} Assessing the stability across randomized episodes.
    \item \textbf{Zero-Impact Consistency:} Based on the \textbf{Red Impact Count}, tracking whether the adversary successfully executed its final impact goal.
    \item \textbf{Hallucination Rate:} The percentage of invalid actions, including those caught and corrected by the CoSC gate.
\end{itemize}



