\section{Critical Analysis}
The experiments reveal a clear correlation between internal reasoning capabilities and long-term strategic resilience. 

\textbf{The Reasoning Advantage:} DeepSeek-R1-1.5b, despite being a smaller model, outperformed the larger Qwen-2.5-7b in the 500-step horizon. This is attributed to DeepSeek's native "Chain-of-Thought" processing, which demonstrated higher resilience to accumulated state uncertainty. The CoSC gate was particularly effective here, successfully repairing 56\% of errors and preventing the agent from "paralyzing" during high-pressure attack phases.

\textbf{Consistency vs. Scale:} Qwen-2.5-7b exhibited near-perfect instruction adherence with a total hallucination rate of only 2.6\% and zero syntactic errors. However, its lower mean reward suggests a more conservative defensive posture compared to DeepSeek’s proactive remediation.

% --- ADD THE NEW SUBSECTION HERE ---
\subsection{Behavioral Consistency Analysis}
To further evaluate the reliability of our proposed architecture, we analyze the \textbf{Stability Coefficient} ($C_v$), defined as the ratio of the standard deviation to the absolute mean reward ($C_v = \frac{\sigma}{|\mu|}$). This metric serves as a normalized indicator of volatility; a lower value indicates that the agent's performance is predictable and consistent across different episodes.

As illustrated in Figure \ref{fig:stability_coefficient}, the original baseline model (All-LLM) from Castro et al. [1] exhibits a high coefficient, reflecting the stochastic and often hallucinatory nature of unconstrained LLMs in complex cyber environments. In contrast, both our \textbf{DeepSeek-R1} and \textbf{Qwen-2.5} implementations, hardened by the \textbf{CoSC semantic gate}, achieve stability levels that closely mirror the specialized \textbf{KEEP RL Expert}. 

This result is a significant milestone: it proves that through logical reinforcement and real-time self-correction, LLMs can overcome their inherent unpredictability to function as reliable, production-ready defenders in a multi-agent SOC environment.

\begin{figure}[h]
    \centering
    \includegraphics[width=\columnwidth]{04_stability_coefficient.png}
    \caption{Stability Coefficient ($C_v$) comparison.}
    \label{fig:stability_coefficient}
\end{figure}

\textbf{Red Impact Suppression:} Most notably, both agents maintained a \textbf{zero-impact count} throughout the strict evaluation. This proves that logic-hardened LLMs can reliably block lateral movement and privilege escalation in an enterprise network, a feat previously reserved for deterministic RL policies.

\section{Conclusion}
This study validates that modern Large Language Models, when equipped with a preventative \textbf{Chain-of-Self-Correction (CoSC)} mechanism, can achieve performance parity with specialized Reinforcement Learning experts. Our \textbf{DeepSeek-R1-1.5b} implementation reached a new state-of-the-art benchmark for LLM agents in the CybORG environment, yielding an 81\% improvement over original baselines and effectively containing all red agent impact attempts across 1,000 steps. These findings demonstrate that "logical hardening" and local high-performance inference are the essential components for transitioning LLMs into production-ready Autonomous Cyber Defense (ACD) systems.

%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%
%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%%

\section{Practical Cybersecurity Impact}
The transition of Large Language Models from generative assistants to autonomous decision-makers introduces a paradigm shift for enterprise Security Operations Centers (SOC). The architecture presented in this study resolves several critical barriers to real-world deployment.

\subsection{Explainable Incident Response and the Thought Trace}
Traditional RL models function as "black boxes," issuing defensive commands without justification. This opacity is unacceptable in a live enterprise environment where actions like \texttt{Restore} or \texttt{BlockTrafficZone} severely disrupt business continuity. Our hybrid ACD system replaces raw numerical outputs with a natural language "Thought Trace." Because the CoSC semantic gate actively filters out logical hallucinations, SOC analysts can interact with a smart alert system that not only isolates a compromised host but provides a verifiable, step-by-step rationale grounded in specific Indicators of Compromise (IOCs). This transforms the AI from a black-box actor into an accountable digital team member.

\subsection{Data Privacy and Air-Gapped Execution}
A fundamental flaw in previous LLM-based ACD research has been the reliance on proprietary, cloud-hosted APIs (e.g., GPT-4). Sending sensitive network telemetry, topology details, and vulnerability states to external servers violates basic operational security principles. By achieving RL-parity with small, heavily quantized models (DeepSeek-R1-1.5b and Qwen-2.5-7b) running on local infrastructure, we demonstrate the viability of "Private Autonomous Defense." Operating on local hardware allows the ACD system to function within heavily restricted or entirely air-gapped environments, ensuring that strategic defensive logic and proprietary network data never leave the corporate perimeter.

\section{Future Research Directions}
While the integration of the Chain-of-Self-Correction (CoSC) mechanism successfully bridged the performance gap between LLMs and RL agents, this study opens several promising avenues for future exploration:

\begin{itemize}
    \item \textbf{Multi-Agent LLM Debates:} Future architectures could implement a "Council of Defenders" where models with different inductive biases collaborate. For instance, an architecture where a reasoning-focused model (e.g., DeepSeek) proposes a remediation strategy, while an instruction-following model (e.g., Qwen) acts as the semantic gatekeeper to validate the proposal against rigid enterprise policies before execution.
    
    \item \textbf{Self-Evolving Prompts and Context Distillation:} Instead of static system prompts, the agent could utilize episodic memory to autonomously rewrite its own defensive heuristics after a failed simulation. This self-evolution would allow the LLM to learn from Red Agent bypasses, dynamically adjusting its IOC-priority weighting without requiring manual prompt engineering.
    
    \item \textbf{RL-to-LLM Behavioral Distillation:} Given that pure RL agents still exhibit faster Mean Time to Remediate (MTTR), future work should explore fine-tuning local LLMs directly on the highest-reward trajectories generated by agents like KEEP. This would infuse the LLM's transformer weights with optimal sub-network routing heuristics, combining RL efficiency with LLM explainability.
\end{itemize}

